ce:section.ce:para:
We further carried out density functional theory (DFT) calculations on compounds THH1 and THH2 at the B3LYP/6-31 G (d) level based on optimized geometric structures using the Gaussian 09 program (Fig. 2
                        ). As shown in Table 1
                        , the electron density of the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) for THH1 and THH2 were mainly localized over the electron-donating moiety (part2), with substituted thienyl and phenyl groups and interfacing helicene fragments. The charge contributions of atoms in part2 fragments were up to 94.8% for THH1 and 93.0% for THH2. However, the electron density of the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) for both part2 of two compounds were localized predominantly on the imides (46.9% for THH1 and 50.3% for THH2). These indicated that THH1 and THH2 both had obvious tendency to twist intramolecular charge transfer (TICT) from thienyl and phenyl groups to imides [30]. Meanwhile, from the Table S2, it could be found that the estimated dipole moments of first excited state (2.75 Debye for THH1 and 3.05 Debye for THH2) were larger than the ground-state respectively (2.13 Debye for THH1 and 2.41 Debye for THH2), which could cause significant solvatochromism. Therefore, the energy of the excited state could be reduced by the interaction between dipole moment of dye molecules and the polar solvent molecules [31]. As a result, the fluorescence emission of dyes was at lower energies or longer wavelength with the solvent polarity increasing.
